column1: 13900028,,2023-10-03T11:19:24Z,low,Nice stream with good flow. Railway crossings approximately 30 m upstream are much more of a barrier then the crossing on Penny Street.," Very small road and pipe. Not much road fill above pipe,  in decent condition.          "," Because of the very small amount of road fill and the large size of this stream,  a flood would likely wash out the road if a significant volume of water made it through the railway crossing upstream. Townsite of Penny is up the road with some residences beyond so people could be stranded as this is the only access.          ","Assuming fish bearing due to low gradients and proximity to the Fraser river. column1: 13905537,,2023-10-03T11:38:41Z,medium,"Three pipes at 0.9 m each, but only one has flowing water,  other two are blocked by vegetation. Made of concrete and built in 1930. Nice stream with good flow. Abundant rearing habitat located upstream.  Although the stream has a lot of volume, the depth in the one pipe functioning is extremely shallow and has a 50cm concrete drop at the outlet.  This road is the only access to the town of Penny just downstream, therefore a wash out could leave them stranded.",Inlet of two of the three pipes blocked by sediment with vegetation growing on it.          ,"Near the remote community of Penny,  there is a residence immediately downstream of the road on the left bank.          ","Assuming fish bearing do to gradients and proximity to the Fraser river. Because it’s on the railway,  all work extremely is expensive and complicated. Townsite of Penny is farther down this road with this as the only access so if the railway culvert were to allow enough water to wipe out Penny Street,  residents downstream could be stranded.          ",,,,,,,,13905537,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,,Tributary to Fraser River,Railway ,,CN Rail,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,2.7,20,,2023-10-03,10,612146,5967655,No,,No,No,,7,0.5,0.3,No,2.5,3.3,0.5,No,No,Deep Fill,Medium,,,,,,,,,,,,newgraph_airvine,1,1,2,4,1,1,1,5,1,10,2,1,10,8,32,37,20231003_114044.jpg,20231003_114104.jpg,20231003_114151.jpg,20231003_114110.jpg,20231003_114058.jpg,20231003_114115.jpg,,,20231003_114220.jpg,,20231003_114225.jpg,20231003_114231.jpg,Age,Card,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 13903452,,2023-10-03T13:38:13Z,high, Very nice stream with abundant gravels and good flow upstream. Some old growth cedar within the upstream riparian area. Penny Road is only access in and out of the community of Penny.  Unassessed railway crossing ~300m upstream.,"Pipe must be bent in the middle, because cannot see through. ","Large outlet drop, deep outlet pool, large channel width indicate pipe is very undersized and at risk of flooding.     ",Assuming fish bearng due to gradients and proximity to the Fraser river. ",Backwatering of this structure may be due to the railway located downstream.          ,"Very large channel with with large bridge located on River Road just upstream indicates these pipes may be well undersized. ","Stream flows into crossing from the east, flowing along the ditch for approximately 60 to 70 m. Very nice stream with good flow abundant gravels and some pools to 50 cm deep. inlet is completely buried as outlet is blocked by beaver debris. Culvert slope estimated. 09:31:27","The crossing is actually located ~150m south of the modelled crossing (at km 31.9), on an unmapped Freshwater Atlas stream which flows into the crossing from the east, flowing along the ditch for approximately 60-70m. The streamline can be seen in satellite imagery. Very nice stream with good flow, abundant gravels, and some pools to 50cm deep. The inlet is completely buried and the outlet is blocked by beaver debris. Culvert slope estimated. 09:31:27",false,

column1: 13903179,,2023-10-04T13:44:19Z,low,"Horsetail and willow wetland upstream with a small well-defined channel with fine gradients. Pipe is blocked by beaver debris. There’s a second pipe that’s approximately 1.5 m higher and 0.9m in diameter that is free of debris and functions as an overflow. Potential refuge area during periods of high flow in the Fraser river,  which was only 40m downstream at the time of assessment.  Gate at the end of the road preventing access to launch point for Penny.  Could consider road deactivation as a solution.  Crossing is located in the Ancient Forest/Chun T'oh Whudujut Protected Area.        ", Primary pipe is 100% blocked by beaver debris with small trickle coming through. Secondary pipe 0.9 m in diameter is located approximately 1.5 m higher in elevation and it’s clear of debris,Secondary drainage pipe may be sufficient to drain this area in flood event. Potential refuge area during periods of high flow in the Fraser river, which was only 40m downstream at the time of assessment. Gate at the end of the road preventing access to launch point for Penny. Could consider road deactivation as a solution. Crossing is located in the Ancient Forest/Chun T'oh Whudujut Protected Area. Ministry of Transportation chris_culvert_id: 1993423. 13:44:19",false,

column1: 22200082,,2023-10-05T09:47:05Z,medium,Stream is mostly dewater. Large beaver dam (1.7m high) located approximately 30m upstream. Fully embedded pipe with beaver grate on the inlet.  Unassessed crossing on private driveway upstream from here. Adjacent landowner has concerns about the recent lack of water and says it is un-characteristic for the section of stream. They have concerns that recent pipeline construction just upstream of this crossing has potentially influenced beaver populations and water flow.,Pipe and road prism in good shape.          ,"Wetland areas could moderate a flood event but the pipe is very undersized so it may washout the road, but with minor implications as there are multiple access routes and this is a somewhat rural area.          ","Assuming fish bearing due to gradients and proximity to known fish points. Paved road, but narrow with small amounts of road fill so construction would be quite straightforward.          ",,,,,,,,22200082,,newgraph_airvine,newgraph_airvine,383,Cranberry Creek ,Cranberry Lake Road ,,MOTI,Closed Bottom Structure,Round Culvert,,0.75,12.5,,2023-10-05,11,345873,5855411,Yes,0.18,Yes,No,,1,0,0,No,0,4,0,Yes,No,Deep Fill,Medium,,,,,,,,,,,,newgraph_airvine,1,1,1,3,2,2,4,7,2,3,8,8,10,9,40,47,20231005_094950.jpg,20231005_094959.jpg,20231005_095015.jpg,20231005_095003.jpg,20231005_094953.jpg,20231005_095012.jpg,,,,,20231005_095038.jpg,20231005_103126.jpg,Beaver dam,Upstream wetland,"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN"" ""http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd"">

column1: 22200081,,2023-10-05T12:14:12Z,medium, Two pipes at 1.4m diameter each. Crossing is only 5m downstream of the railway crossing. The stream has bigger volume of water at this location than it did below Highway 5 downstream.  Water may be recharging beaver influenced wetlands downstream. Road edge has been armoured with riprap and downstream side of road bank is eroding significantly for approximately 60m.           ,Upstream side of road appears to have failed and been repaired with riprap and asphalt patch. Downstream of the crossing for approximately 60m there is significant erosion along Loseth Road.          ,Seems likely that a flood event could impact culvert as the upstream pipe under the railway is well under sized and there has already been some failure of the road surface at this location. Small road with multiple access routes so consequences may not be that severe. Beaver influenced wetlands downstream could help buffer flows before incident at Highway 5.          ,"Small paved road with not a lot of road fill,  however,  intersects with railway immediately upstream which would create complications and additional expenses. column1: 22200061,,2023-10-05T22:39:24Z,low,"Large stream with cobble boulder substrate suitable for bull trout. Concrete box culvert is 60% embedded on the downstream side. column1: 22200067,,2023-10-05T15:53:19Z,mod,Pipes and road are in extremely poor condition with evidence of embankment failure and pipes rusted all the way through on the bottom side in places. Small side road parallel to Highway 16 with residences that could be accessed from either side. Removal of crossing could perhaps be considered. Large high value system suitable for bulltrout rearing.  Culvert upstream is relatively new concrete box culvert on the highway which is over half embedded and 3.7m wide. ,Pipes and road are in incredibly poor condition with evidence of road failing and corrosion all the way through the bottom in places on both pipes. Riprap placed upstream to try to protect the road. The structure is definitely at the end of its life.          ," Although a flood event is highly likely to blow out the road at this location, there are only private residences on either side with potentially Rotarian, in good condition that could help buffer flows, and limit damage downstream.          ","Assumed fish being due to gradients. Because this road accesses the highway on either side, residences could be accessed without the crossing in place.  There’s a large volume of water, but the amount of fill is small. Removal of this crossing could potentially be considered.
